    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1979-10-02T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1979-10-02T00:00:00-05:00" n="481"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d481">
                <head>481. Memorandum From the President’s Assistant for National Security Affairs
                        (<persName corresp="#p_BZ_1">Brzezinski</persName>) to Secretary of State
                        <persName corresp="#p_VC_1">Vance</persName>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d481fn1">Source: Carter Library, National
                        Security Affairs, Brzezinski Material, Country File, Box 46, Latin America:
                        10/1–14/79. Secret. <persName corresp="#p_OHD_1">Owen</persName> wrote at
                        the top of the memorandum: “John pls call me. <persName corresp="#p_OHD_1"
                            >H. Owen</persName>.”</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1979-10-02">October 2, 1979</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Economic Security Assistance for Central America and the Caribbean
                        (U)</item>
                </list>
                <p>In response to your memorandum of September 28, the President has approved your
                    seeking immediate <gloss target="#t_FY_1">FY</gloss> 1980 supplemental <gloss
                        target="#t_ESF_1">ESF</gloss> authorization and appropriation of $75 million
                    to help cover Nicaragua’s balance of payments gap in 1980.<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d481fn2">
                        <persName corresp="#p_VC_1">Vance</persName>’s September 28 memorandum to
                        Carter requested that the administration increase the $145 million budget
                        request for Central America by $30.6 million “to address immediate and
                        urgent requirements in the Caribbean.” The memorandum is printed as <ref
                            target="frus1977-80v23#d365">Document 365</ref> in <ref
                            target="frus1977-80v23">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations,</hi> 1977–1980, vol. XXIII, Mexico,
                            Cuba, and the Caribbean</ref>.</note> Consideration of whether such
                    assistance is required in 1981 will be deferred to the <gloss target="#t_FY_1"
                        >FY</gloss> 1981 budget process. (S)</p>
                <p>With regard to Honduras, El Salvador, and the Caribbean, the President has
                    decided not to seek supplementals for these countries. Instead, the United
                    States will support multilateral development efforts to be organized by the
                    World Bank at the request of these countries. Subject to progress on democratic
                    reforms, we will increase planned <gloss target="#t_FY_1">FY</gloss> 1981
                    development assistance to them. (S)</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_BZ_1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Zbigniew Brzezinski</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
